With the growing demands for user privacy protection, a variety of biometric user authentication mechanisms has been continuously developed. However, their performance evaluations are often conducted on limited population scales, sometimes involving as few as a dozen users. Whether such constrained evaluations can fully capture the true potential of these authentication mechanisms remains uncertain. To mitigate the impact of this issue, our study begins by exploring the feature subspace separability of user biometric data, thereby introducing the crucial role of population scale in shaping performance evaluations. Drawing on these insights, we develop a conditional generative adversarial network-based data generation framework tailored to synthesize "unseen user" data, to enlarge the evaluation population scale. Moreover, it incorporates spatial occupancy and distinguishability metrics as optimization objectives, striving for the generated data to closely align with real data distribution characteristics. Experimental results indicate that the performance of emerging authentication mechanisms exhibits variations as the user base grows: the recognition accuracy increases when generated data is included in the training set but decreases when such data is allocated to the test set. In general, our work facilitates a dynamic analysis of how performance evolves as user populations grow, providing deeper insights into the identity recognition ability of proposed authentication mechanisms.